@rhatdan This PR is stuck for what information is expected in this tree command. 

If the information which all previous layers of given image is fine, I guess this PR is output wise working. Though the performance improvement is required as suggested by @mtrmac.

Also, I am not clear on the comments, the parent layer can be retured as _nil_, if there is no coresponding image present. I think to prepare a rootfs from Image, we need all layers to be present in local registry and if layers are present in local registry, _Parent_ layer should be reachable.

@kunalkushwaha What is the state of this PR?
bot, retest this please
@vbatts @runcom @fatherlinux Could you guys comment on the output of the command.

> @rhatdan dumb question. How do I compile a version of podman with this patch?

@fatherlinux, I keep forgetting the commands, so I use the following bash script (named checkoutpr) in my path: https://paste.fedoraproject.org/paste/A7HiwT~2aY3~STQCwplS9A

You can run `checkoutpr $remote 1642` with $remote being the git-remote you want to pull from. The script will fetch the PR and check it out in your local git tree.

- Updated test-case to make it fast and skip for remote test.
- Updated man pages with current output.

@mtrmac I feel consistent behaviour in both case i.e. with and without `--whatrequires` will be less confusing for user.

//cc @vrothberg PTAL

@kunalkushwaha I understand that. Sorry for the inconvenience but we need to print a tree.

I recommend using https://github.com/xlab/treeprint, where we use `AddNode()` for the first child-node (i.e., index == 0) and and `AddBranch()` for the child-nodes with index >= 1.

The tree formatting will happen implicitly.

I've been experimenting a bit. Please have a look at the following output:
```
[valentin@nebuchadnezzar libpod]$ ./bin/podman image tree --whatrequires ae96a4ad4f3f
Image ID: ae96a4ad4f3f
Tags:    [docker.io/library/ruby:latest]
Size:    894.2MB
Image Layers
ID: 9c92106221c7 Size:  2.56kB Top Layer of: [docker.io/library/ruby:latest]
├─ ID: 2d8fa4a92bf9 Size: 3.584kB
│  └─ ID: f5fa125fec18 Size: 169.5MB
│     └─ ID: 16ece66f18da Size: 2.048kB
│        └─ ID: 2c7e0228860b Size: 3.957MB
│           └─ ID: dee4bb778f4c Size: 164.7MB
│              └─ ID: aaa5307e91ef Size: 11.75MB
│                 └─ ID: c5b55d20cfba Size: 8.532MB
│                    └─ ID: f5ee3209dfbc Size: 1.141MB Top Layer of: [docker.io/circleci/ruby:latest]
└─ ID: 6a810e045772 Size:  2.56kB Top Layer of: [localhost/foo:bar]
```

It looks similar to the current implementation. Ultimately, I would prefer to avoid cascading and merge such linear branches but that can be deferred to future work.

For the usual case (without --whatrequires) we can safely avoid cascading by adding nodes with index >= 1 as children of node[0].

I've been using github.com/shivamMg/ppds (as it seemed to me to have the most sane API) with the following patch:
```diff
diff --git a/cmd/podman/tree.go b/cmd/podman/tree.go
index 1655dc06d725..7c3fdb408eb5 100644
--- a/cmd/podman/tree.go
+++ b/cmd/podman/tree.go
@@ -10,6 +10,7 @@ import (
 	units "github.com/docker/go-units"
 	"github.com/pkg/errors"
 	"github.com/spf13/cobra"
+	"github.com/shivamMg/ppds/tree"
 )

 var (
@@ -102,15 +103,32 @@ func treeCmd(c *cliconfig.TreeValues) error {
 		// the layers will be filled such that
 		// (Start)TopLayer->...intermediate Child Layer(s)-> Child TopLayer(End)
 		//             (Forks)... intermediate Child Layer(s) -> Child Top Layer(End)
-		err := printImageChildren(imageInfo, layerInfoMap, img.TopLayer(), 0)
+		node, err := printImageChildren(imageInfo, layerInfoMap, img.TopLayer(), 0)
 		if err != nil {
 			return err
 		}
+		tree.PrintHrn(node)
 	}

 	return nil
 }

+type Node struct {
+	data     string
+	children []*Node
+}
+
+func (n *Node) Data() interface{} {
+	return n.data
+}
+
+func (n *Node) Children() (c []tree.Node) {
+	for _, child := range n.children {
+		c = append(c, tree.Node(child))
+	}
+	return
+}
+
 // Stores hierarchy of images such that all parent layers using which image is built are stored in imageInfo
 // Layers are added such that  (Start)RootLayer->...intermediate Parent Layer(s)-> TopLayer(End)
 func buildImageHierarchyMap(imageInfo *infoImage, layerMap map[string]*image.LayerInfo, layerID string) error {
@@ -133,30 +151,28 @@ func buildImageHierarchyMap(imageInfo *infoImage, layerMap map[string]*image.Lay
 // Layers are stored as follows
 // (Start)TopLayer->...intermediate Child Layer(s)-> Child TopLayer(End)
 //             (Forks)... intermediate Child Layer(s) -> Child Top Layer(End)
-func printImageChildren(imageInfo *infoImage, layerMap map[string]*image.LayerInfo, layerID string, scope int) error {
+func printImageChildren(imageInfo *infoImage, layerMap map[string]*image.LayerInfo, layerID string, scope int) (*Node, error) {
 	if layerID == "" {
-		return nil
+		return nil, nil
 	}
 	ll, ok := layerMap[layerID]
 	if !ok {
-		return fmt.Errorf("lookup error: layerid  %s, not found", layerID)
-	}
-
-	for p := 0; p < scope; p++ {
-		fmt.Printf(" ")
+		return nil, fmt.Errorf("lookup error: layerid  %s, not found", layerID)
 	}
 	tags := ""
 	if len(ll.RepoTags) > 0 {
 		tags = fmt.Sprintf("Top Layer of: %s", ll.RepoTags)
 	}
-	fmt.Printf("└─ ID: %s Size: %7v %s\n", ll.ID[:12], units.HumanSizeWithPrecision(float64(ll.Size), 4), tags)
-	scope++
+	children := []*Node{}
 	for _, childID := range ll.ChildID {
-		if err := printImageChildren(imageInfo, layerMap, childID, scope); err != nil {
-			return err
+		node, err := printImageChildren(imageInfo, layerMap, childID, scope)
+		if err != nil {
+			return nil, err
 		}
+		children = append(children, node)
 	}
-	return nil
+	data := fmt.Sprintf("ID: %s Size: %7v %s", ll.ID[:12], units.HumanSizeWithPrecision(float64(ll.Size), 4), tags)
+	return &Node{data: data, children: children}, nil
 }

 // prints the layers info of image
```
